                    <div class="question">Why is it called "Basecoat"?</div>
                    <div class="answer">When artists paint on a canvas, they first apply a basecoat of primer to it. This basecoat serves as a neutral color and as a structure for further paint coats to glide over the canvas and provide support that allows the painting to stand the test of time. A paint coat can be the background colors, the highlights or a clear protective coating in the end.</div>
                    <div class="answer">This is exactly the purpose of this framework, to provide the least amount of style possible that offers an aesthetically pleasing result that can be easily enhanced with few additional styles.</div>

                    <div class="question">What are coats?</div>
                    <div class="answer">Short answer... coats are themes, but a special kind of theme.</div>
                    <div class="answer">They can be mixed and stacked on top of each other to match your needs.</div>
                    <div class="answer">As with art, in css you can apply coats to basecoat. These coats can make your elements rounded, change the color palette, change the typography or even add a functionality like a date picker.</div>

                    <div class="question">Won't having many coats make my site slow?</div>
                    <div class="answer">Yes, any site with too much css and/or js will eventually get slow. That is why Basecoat aims to be as simple an minimalistic as possible so that you can add a couple of coats on top of it.</div>
                    <div class="answer">This approach ensures that the styles you add via coats are styles you need. Instead of a huge framework with tons of styles you will not use or will have a hard time overwriting. In every case, concatenating Basecoat and its coats is highly recommended.</div>

